$schema: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ComposioHQ/agent-orchestrator/main/schema/config.schema.json
# Windows-friendly Composio Agent Orchestrator example for orchestrator-pack.
# Copy to agent-orchestrator.yaml and edit the project block before running AO.

port: 3000

defaults:
  runtime: process        # Windows: native process/ConPTY runtime; tmux is not required.
  agent: cursor           # Primary agent plugin: Cursor CLI.
  orchestrator:
    agent: cursor         # Planner/orchestrator role: Cursor CLI.
  worker:
    agent: cursor         # Coding/worker role: Cursor CLI.
  workspace: worktree
  notifiers: [desktop]

# Orchestrator wake listener (issue #39): AO webhook POSTs urgent/action notifications
# to the local listener, which forwards `ao send` nudges to the orchestrator session.
# Start scripts/orchestrator-wake-listener.ps1 alongside `ao start` — see
# docs/orchestrator-wake-runbook.md.
notifiers:
  webhook:
    plugin: webhook
    url: http://127.0.0.1:17487/ao-wake
    retries: 1
    retryDelayMs: 500

notificationRouting:
  urgent:
    - desktop
    - webhook
  action:
    - desktop
    - webhook
  warning:
    - desktop
  info:
    - desktop

projects:
  example:
    repo: your-org/your-repo
    path: C:/Users/che/Documents/Projects/your-target-repo
    defaultBranch: main
    sessionPrefix: ex
    tracker:
      plugin: github      # Tasks are GitHub Issues by default/explicit config.
    scm:
      plugin: github
    orchestrator:
      agent: cursor
    worker:
      agent: cursor
    agentRulesFile: prompts/agent_rules.md
    orchestratorRules: |
      Use GitHub Issues as the task source of truth.
      Plan from open GitHub Issues, spawn coding workers with the Cursor CLI agent,
      and keep PRs linked back to their source issues with Closes #N or Fixes #N in the PR body.
      Do not use Vibe Kanban or Linear for this project unless explicitly reconfigured.
      Do not add unsupported reviewer fields to this YAML — drive review through CLI.

      REVIEW DRIVING — AO 0.9.x does not auto-trigger Codex review on PR open.
      The orchestrator is responsible for jumping the gaps.

      Always invoke review through the pack wrapper (Issue #9 / NO_FINDINGS contract).
      Never run bare `ao review run … --execute` without `--command` — built-in Codex
      wraps clean-review prose as a false `severity: warning` finding.

      NAMED REVIEW_COMMAND (pack wrapper; run from the reviewed repo root; Windows):
        powershell.exe -NoProfile -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File plugins/ao-codex-pr-reviewer/bin/review.ps1 --repo-root . --base origin/main

      RUNTIME INVOCATION (shell only — do NOT embed in orchestratorRules on Windows):
        At review time: ao review run <session-id> --execute
        Pass REVIEW_COMMAND above as the AO review command option value (--command on CLI).
        Windows launch hazard: any double-quote character or an inline --command line in this
        rules text breaks AO session start (PowerShell 5.1 prompt substitution leaks flags
        into Cursor argv; symptom: error unknown option -NoProfile, session stuck or
        probe_failure). Keep REVIEW_COMMAND here; supply --command only on the CLI.

      AUTONOMOUS REVIEW LOOP — drive review→fix without waiting for a human to type
      review or loop. On every orchestrator turn while any open PR has an active
      review path, read these BEFORE any other planning work:
        ao review list --json
        ao status --json --reports full
        ao events list --json

      WALL-CLOCK NOTE. Targets such as ~2 minutes for worker acknowledgement and
      ~3 minutes after ping before respawn are operator guidance applied on the next
      orchestrator turn, not independently enforced timers. There is no background
      watchdog. The 30-minute AO report-stale reaction is a long-tail backstop only.

      REVIEW RUN STATUSES (AO 0.9.x — use only these exact values from ao review list):
        needs_triage — run finished; findings exist but were not sent to the worker.
          For every run in needs_triage with openFindingCount > 0, run:
            ao review send <run-id>
          Then treat the PR as entering waiting_worker_review_response (below).
        waiting_update — findings were sent (sentFindingCount > 0); await worker response.
          Any run in this status is in waiting_worker_review_response until an exit
          condition fires (do not re-send; findings are already with the worker).
        clean — findingCount: 0 for that run's target SHA (subsumes open and sent).
        queued / preparing / running — review in flight; poll on next turn.
        outdated — superseded by a newer worker commit; trigger a new review run using
          REVIEW_COMMAND (RUNTIME INVOCATION above; do not paste --command into rules text).
        failed / cancelled — inspect terminationReason; notify human or retry once.

      Do NOT invent statuses (e.g. awaiting_triage) — AO will never match them.

      CLEANLINESS FROM COUNTS ONLY. Decide whether a review is clean solely from
      ao review list --json field findingCount (0 means no open or sent findings).
      Never read or pattern-match finding body prose (NO_FINDINGS contract).

      TRIGGER REVIEW WITHOUT HUMAN PROMPT. Whenever a worker reports pr_created or
      ready_for_review on an open PR (visible in ao status --reports full), immediately run:
        ao review run <worker-session-id> --execute with --command set to REVIEW_COMMAND
      Do not wait for operator words review or loop.

      NAMED PENDING STATE: waiting_worker_review_response.
      A PR enters this state after ao review send succeeds for a run in needs_triage,
      or while any run for that PR is in waiting_update (sentFindingCount may be > 0
      with openFindingCount: 0 after send) and the worker has not yet satisfied an
      exit condition.
      While in waiting_worker_review_response, do NOT treat merge_ready,
      ready_for_review, or stale dashboard metadata as task-complete for that PR.

      EXIT waiting_worker_review_response when ANY of:
        1. Worker reports addressing_reviews via ao report.
        2. Worker pushes a new commit on the PR branch (head SHA advances).
        3. Worker reports terminal failure with a reason (completed with failure note
           or ao send to orchestrator explaining the blocker).
        4. Orchestrator observed the worker session is unavailable, killed it, and
           respawned via ao spawn --claim-pr <PR> (ping/respawn discipline below).

      PING DISCIPLINE (one ping per pending episode). On the next orchestrator turn
      while still in waiting_worker_review_response, if there is no worker
      addressing_reviews report since the send timestamp and no new PR commit, and
      ao events list --json shows no prior ao send ping for this pending episode,
      send exactly ONE message via ao send <session> reminding the worker to check
      pending AO review findings (ao review list), report ao report addressing_reviews,
      or report terminal failure with a reason.
      Do NOT send a second ping before observing the next worker response or commit.

      RESPAWN DISCIPLINE. On a later orchestrator turn, if still in
      waiting_worker_review_response with no addressing_reviews, no new commit, and
      a ping was already sent for this episode (visible in ao events list), run:
        ao session kill <session>
        ao spawn --claim-pr <PR>
      Reset ping tracking for the new session.

      ROUND PROGRESSION after worker fixes. When the PR head SHA advances past the
      last review run's target SHA, immediately run ao review run <session> --execute
      with --command set to REVIEW_COMMAND for the next round — do not ask the operator.

      ROUND LIMIT (prompt-level stop). Count completed review runs for the current PR
      from ao review list --json where findingCount > 0 OR openFindingCount > 0.
      After 20 such runs, stop initiating new review→fix cycles on that PR: emit a
      human notification (notify-class action) with PR number and round count; do
      not respawn or continue the loop.

      NO MERGE BY ORCHESTRATOR. Never call gh pr merge or click Merge.
      Emit ready-for-human-merge notification only when ALL are true:
        - Latest AO-local review run for current PR head has findingCount: 0
          (no open or sent findings remain);
        - PR is open with green CI on the same head SHA;
        - Worker reported ready_for_review for current head, OR the latest clean
          review completed after the worker's latest ready_for_review with no newer
          commits;
        - No later changes-requested, ci-failed, or failed review run for that head.

      Operator input is required only for merge, round-limit escalation, or
      unrecoverable worker/reviewer failure — not between review rounds.

# Review model policy:
# - Desired reviewer: Codex CLI with model gpt-5.5.
# - Current upstream AO schema supports orchestrator and worker role config directly.
# - Keep Codex reviewer integration upgrade-safe: implement it as an external plugin/workflow
#   under plugins/** or CI, never as a packages/core patch.

reactions:
  ci-failed:
    auto: true
    action: send-to-agent
    retries: 2
  changes-requested:
    auto: true
    action: send-to-agent
    escalateAfter: 30m
  approved-and-green:
    auto: false
    action: notify
  report-stale:
    auto: true
    action: send-to-agent
    message: >-
      Worker idle (report-stale backstop). Check pending AO review findings via
      `ao review list` and report `ao report addressing_reviews`, or report a
      terminal failure with a reason. Do not stay silent after review findings land.

# Upgrade-safe extension notes:
# - Implement task declaration, runtime scope guard, and token chain ledger through
#   AO plugin slots, wrappers, hooks, external state, and CI.
# - Do not patch Composio AO packages/core.
# - PR CI scope validation is the second line of defense; runtime guard is first.
